79df2f53-13a4-4121-8e5b-e753e4d0bbfa.1ed60182-cdb7-4822-b7bb-98e48022dbbc.description=This operation iterates through a string that contains an array in the JavaScript Object Notation format (JSON). Each time this operation is called, it places the value of the current array element into the "returnResult" output and advances the iterator to the next array element. The JSON format is used to encode arrays and other values using JavaScript notation. For arrays, this means that the values need to be enclosed by square brackets, and each element in the array can be a string (enclosed by quotes), a number, true, false, null, or nested array or object. Commas are always used as delimiters between array elements, and they can also appear within string elements. The benefits of JavaScript arrays are that delimiters are fixed and cannot be confused with data, and that complex nesting of arrays and objects are supported. The description of the enclosing folder, /Library/Utility Operations/Container/JavaScript Objects has more examples, and the JSON format is described completely at http\://www.json.org. Inputs\: array - The JavaScript array that will be iterated through. A normal OO list is NOT a JavaScript array. Examples\: For example, the following is a simple JSON array\: [ "cat", "dog", "horse" ] The equivalent OO list (that is not a JavaScript array) is\: cat,dog,horse Results\: returnResult - This is the primary output and contains the current array element or an exception message if something went wrong. When incorporating this operation into a flow, you should assign a meaningful result value from this field. Responses\: has more - The iterator has not yet reached the end of the array. The "returnResult" output will be populated with the value of the current element in the array, and the iterator will advance to the next element in the array. no more - The iterator has reached the end of the array, and there is no more data to return. The iterator will become undefined after this call, which basically will reset it so that if called again, this operation will begin another iteration at the beginning of the array. failure - There was some error in iterating through the list, and the "returnResult" output will contain information about the error. This will occur if the input array is not a valid JavaScript array. You may wish to use a tool such as http\://www.jsonlint.com/ to help diagnose problems with JavaScript Object Notation. Notes\: 1. Modifying the contents of the array during iteration is not supported unless the iteration has finished. 2. The operation supports iterating through nested arrays. 79df2f53-13a4-4121-8e5b-e753e4d0bbfa.3d3f7c2e-979e-4771-9e24-15585d2b20fb.description=
Accepts an object in the JavaScript Object Notation format (JSON) and
returns a value for the specified key.

The JSON format encodes objects as a set of unordered key/value pairs, which is
similar to a structure or map in other programming languages.  For example,
   { "city" \: "Palo Alto", 
     "state" \: "CA" }
is an object with two elements one with the name "city" having the value "Palo
Alto", and the other being the name "state" with the value "CA". This operation would 
return "Palo Alto" if user enters "city" as a key.

If the input object contains JSON array, array index can be used in the key input. For example, 
{ "location"\: [
      {"city"\: "Roseville", "country"\: "United States"},
      {"city"\: "Cluj", "country"\: "Romania"},
      {"city"\: "Yehud", "country"\: "Israel"}]    
}
The operation would return "Roseville" if user enters "location[0].city" as a key.

JavaScript objects are useful for representing structured data, and are
especially when used within an array.  For example, an operation that retrieves
a set of incidents from an external system may return the entire list in one
array of incident objects.  The description of the enclosing folder,
/Library/Utility Operations/Container/JavaScript Objects has more examples, and
the JSON format is described completely at http\://www.json.org.

Inputs

   object
      The JavaScript object.  
      The operation will return a failure if it is not a JavaScript object.

   key
      The key in the object to get the value of.

Responses

   success
      The value was successfully returned for the specified key. 

   failure
      There was some error in processing the object, most likely because the
      object is not in valid JavaScript Object Notation or the specified key does not exist in the object.  
      You may wish to use a tool such as http\://www.jsonlint.com/ to help diagnose problems with
      JavaScript Object Notation.

Outputs

   The primary output will be the value for the specified key in the object.

Note

    If the value in JSON object is in scientific notation, the returned output will be converted to an equivalent decimal number. Ex, 2.9e+1 will be converted to 29.
79df2f53-13a4-4121-8e5b-e753e4d0bbfa.4d8efa61-013b-4cb1-8cf5-e25f566757df.description=
This operation checks whether a string matches another string, using a specific matching rule. The "toMatch" input is the string that is checked for matching the "matchTo" expression. 

Inputs\:
    requestType - The type of request to perform.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the string "Matches" if the "toMatch" string matches the "matchTo" string. Otherwise, it contains the string "Does Not Match".  

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Responses\:
    success
    failure


79df2f53-13a4-4121-8e5b-e753e4d0bbfa.9ca7ed9b-7200-4d33-b5aa-b8e26b53d8ac.description=
This operation iterates through a list of values. It is not recommended to modify the value of the "list" and "separator" inputs during the iteration process.

Inputs\:
    list - The list to iterate through.
    separator - A delimiter separating the list elements.
Default value\: ‘,’ (comma) 

Results\:
    resultString - The current list element (if the response is "has more").

Responses\:
    has more - Another value was found in the list and it has been returned.
    no more - The iterator has gone through the entire list. This response is returned once per list iteration.  A subsequent call to the List iterator operation restarts the list iteration process.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
   The position of the iterator in the list is tracked by each step's unique identifier. Therefore, you can simultaneously iterate through the same list from multiple steps.


79df2f53-13a4-4121-8e5b-e753e4d0bbfa.a602b25a-bed7-4798-9c75-3e111870e648.description=
This operation does not do anything. It can be used to filter flow variables by defining them as inputs and filtering them in the Results tab.

Inputs\:
    field1 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field2 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field3 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field4 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the value of  "field1" as it was specified at input or when filtered. 

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.


79df2f53-13a4-4121-8e5b-e753e4d0bbfa.ed74b31d-3041-4b8f-aad1-b6a700ebb281.description=
Inserts a new name/value property into a JSON object, where the value is a valid JSON string. If the  input is not a valid string representation of a JSON object, the operation fails.

The 'Add Property to Object' operation can be used to add a property with a simple string value. 

Examples\: 
1)
    Inputs\:
        jsonObject\: {}
        newPropertyName\: test
        newPropertyValue\: [1,2,3]
     Result\:
         { "test"\:[1,2,3]}
2)
    Inputs\:
        jsonObject\: {}
        newPropertyName\: test
        newPropertyValue\: {"a"\:"b"}
     Result\:
         { "test"\:{"a"\:"b"}}
3)
    Inputs\:
        jsonObject\: {}
        newPropertyName\: test
        newPropertyValue\: 1
     Result\:
         { "test"\:1}

Inputs\:
    jsonObject - String representation of a JSON object. Objects in JSON are a collection of name value pairs, separated by a colon and surrounded with curly brackets {}. The name must be a string value, and the value can be a single string or any valid JSON object or array.
Examples\: {"one"\:1, "two"\:2}, {"one"\:{"a"\:"a","B"\:"B"}, "two"\:"two", "three"\:[1,2,3.4]}
    newPropertyName - The name of the new property to add to the JSON object. 
Examples\: property1, some_property, another property
    newPropertyValue - The value for the new property. This must be a valid JSON representation of a JavaScript object.
Examples\: 1, {"A"\:"A"}, [1,2,3,4]

Results\:
    Result - The JSON array with the inserted element.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully. See the message in  for details.


79df2f53-13a4-4121-8e5b-e753e4d0bbfa.fef50c15-3794-4985-9027-a82a3fe26609.description=
This operation adds a flow variable to the local context. The variable is available in the current flow and its child flows.

Inputs\:
    keyName - The name of the flow variable to add.
    myValue - The value to assign to the flow variable.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the value of "myValue" input field.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.

Note\:
   If a flow variable with the same name already exists, its value will be overwritten.
